      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Pirro Conviction</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Victoria Cross Kelly letter objects to June 23 article suggesting that women like Westchester County Dist Atty Jeanine Pirro will be judged by success, or lack thereof, of husbands like convicted tax cheat Albert J Pirro (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>By writing that Albert J. Pirro Jr.'s conviction on charges of conspiracy and tax evasion ''jeopardizes'' the ''immediate prospects for higher office'' of his wife, Jeanine F. Pirro, the Westchester County district attorney (front page, June 23), you do a disservice to all women and help perpetuate the myth that women should be judged by the success -- or lack thereof -- of their husbands.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>By writing that Albert J. Pirro Jr.'s conviction on charges of conspiracy and tax evasion ''jeopardizes'' the ''immediate prospects for higher office'' of his wife, Jeanine F. Pirro, the Westchester County district attorney (front page, June 23), you do a disservice to all women and help perpetuate the myth that women should be judged by the success -- or lack thereof -- of their husbands.</p>
        <p>One has to wonder whether you would have made the same comment about Mr. Pirro's future prospects had Mrs. Pirro been the one who was convicted.</p>
        <p>VICTORIA CROSS KELLY  West Caldwell, N.J., June 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
